What’s the difference?

keywords (e.g., "taunt", "divineShield", "charge", "windfury"):
short, static flags that change core rules/UI targeting or per-turn counters. They live on the minion’s state (e.g., boardState[uid].tags.taunt = true) and are enforced by your core systems (RequestQueue, targeting checks, attack limits, damage hooks).
Think: passive capabilities.

effects (objects in effects: [...] with typeGroup + type):
data-driven, event-bound behaviors that run via the registry at specific moments (battlecry, deathrattle, startTurn, endTurn, etc.). You can add lots of effects without changing core code—just extend runEffectPayload and/or register new effect types.
Think: scripts that fire on triggers.

You’ll often use both: e.g., a minion with keywords:["taunt"] (passive rule) and a battlecry effect that draws a card.

Registered keywords (your file)

Below I’ll explain what each registered keyword implies and where it’s enforced.

taunt (static rule)

Purpose: Opponents can’t target face (or other non-taunt minions, depending on your rule) while any enemy Taunt minion is alive.

Enforcement: In your UI/RequestQueue targeting logic: before allowing “attack → player” or “attack → non-taunt minion”, check if the defender has any board unit with tags.taunt === true. If yes, force target to a taunt minion.

Registry handler needed? Not strictly. It’s a board rule, not an event. You can still put helper utilities in the registry if you want (e.g., hasTaunt(defenderPS)), but you already handle this in targeting checks.

charge (static rule)

Purpose: Minion can attack the turn it’s played.

Enforcement: When you place the minion, set hasSummoningSickness=false if it has charge (or set attacksLeft to 1 even on the play turn). Without charge, either prevent attacking on same turn or set attacksLeft=0 until next turnStart.

Registry handler? Typically not; enforced in attack eligibility.

windfury (static rule with a per-turn reset)

Purpose: Minion gets 2 attacks per turn.

Enforcement: Your registry does include a handler:

WINDFURY.onTurnStart sets boardState[uid].attacksLeft = 2 for windfury units, and ensures others default to 1.

Your RequestQueue attack flow should decrement attacksLeft and block when it’s 0.

Note: If you support “Mega-Windfury” etc., you’d extend this.

divineShield (static rule with a damage hook)

Purpose: First time the minion would take damage, prevent that damage and remove the shield.

Enforcement: Your registry does include a handler:

DIVINE_SHIELD.onIncomingDamage({ targetPS, targetUid, amount }) returns { canceled:true } and flips tags.divineShield=false—your damage application must call this hook before applying damage (i.e., a centralized “applyIncomingDamage” function that consults the registry).

Note: Currently your creature vs creature code doesn’t call a “damage pipeline” hook; adding one is recommended so Divine Shield works from all sources (combat, spells, auras).

Trigger keywords (event-driven)

These don’t do anything by themselves; they mean the card has effects tied to lifecycle events. Your registry dispatches based on typeGroup.

battlecry

When: The moment the minion card resolves onto the board.

How: Your registry BATTLECRY.onMinionPlayed(ctx) reads effects and runs each with typeGroup === "battlecry".

Examples: draw cards, deal face damage, buff a friendly minion.

deathrattle

When: Right before the minion is removed from the board due to death.

How: DEATHRATTLE.onMinionDied(ctx) runs effects with typeGroup === "deathrattle".

Examples: summon tokens, deal death damage, buff another unit.

startTurn

When: At the start of the owner’s turn.

How: START_OF_TURN.onTurnStart(ctx) scans that player’s board and runs effects with typeGroup === "startTurn" on each minion that has them.

Examples: passive healing, draw 1, refresh self, random pings.

endTurn (you listed it in Keyword, not implemented yet)

When: End of the owner’s turn.

How: Mirror startTurn with END_OF_TURN.onTurnEnd(ctx), scan board, run typeGroup === "endTurn".

Examples: deal 1 to all enemies, float unused mana, etc.

aura (listed but not implemented in the snippet)

Purpose: Continuous buff/debuff while the aura source is alive.

How: You typically:

apply on minionPlayed,

re-apply on any board change (enter/leave), and

remove on minionDied of the aura source.
For simplicity, many games recompute auras each frame/tick or on every board mutation, rather than trying to incrementally maintain many deltas.

Registered effect types (your runEffectPayload)

You’ve added three concrete types so far; they’re data-driven actions your keywords can invoke.

type: "draw"

Where: Any trigger (battlecry, startTurn, etc.), executed by runEffectPayload.

Behavior: Draws from deckMap.get(caster.id) if hand has room; updates deckSizeSelf.

Fields: count (currently you draw 1 in code; to support count > 1, loop count times).

type: "healFace"

Behavior: Heals player HP (caster by default, or enemy:true to heal opponent).

Fields: amount (clamped to HEALTH_POINTS), enemy boolean to target.

type: "dealFace"

Behavior: Damages player HP (caster or opponent based on enemy).

Fields: amount, enemy.

You can add more effect types (e.g., buffMinion, summon, damageMinion, drawSpecific, discover, gainMana, restoreMana, copy, transform, etc.). Just extend runEffectPayload.